      {
        "id": "4e82462c107f388182b5e8df08533066bffeffa1",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 7362,
          "name": "Ruslan Kashapov",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "ruslan.kashapov@pantheon.tech",
          "username": "rkashapov"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2021-01-18 09:19:45.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nspring framework provides configurable, easy to apply caching\nhttps://docs.spring.io/spring-framework/docs/current/reference/html/integration.html#cache\n\ncurrent implementation contains hard-coded configuration and no cache invalidation mechanism.\nnot reliable",
        "patchset_number": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "63debe5e0ad42523e8b522277d88f25af6a18060",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 6679,
          "name": "Claudio David Gasparini",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "gasparini24@gmail.com",
          "username": "cdgasparini"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2021-01-18 09:44:43.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n> Patch Set 3:\n> \n> spring framework provides configurable, easy to apply caching\n> https://docs.spring.io/spring-framework/docs/current/reference/html/integration.html#cache\n> \n> current implementation contains hard-coded configuration and no cache invalidation mechanism.\n> not reliable\n\nnot sure what do you mean by not \"reliable\".. \nBut indeed we could Caffeine, which has better performance, and supports annotations. that I guess is what you want",
        "patchset_number": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "28ad391e6513dbbb358d1899baf164cae6ca060f",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 6639,
          "name": "Toine Siebelink",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "toine.siebelink@est.tech",
          "username": "ToineSiebelink"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2021-01-18 10:53:14.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nHi Claudio I really like what you are doing and the tests you are have added, but please address my first overall comment,\nI think you are caching the wrong object(s). \nI think we should cache the SchemaContext object as it is very costly to generate and if we cache that we never need the resource files behind it anymore... If think it will be good to ahv a chat about this",
        "patchset_number": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "4da3131f6f75009eaf771505b3a8ce8936085607",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 7362,
          "name": "Ruslan Kashapov",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "ruslan.kashapov@pantheon.tech",
          "username": "rkashapov"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2021-01-18 12:44:05.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1\n\n(1 comment)\n\n> Patch Set 3:\n> \n> > Patch Set 3:\n> > \n> > spring framework provides configurable, easy to apply caching\n> > https://docs.spring.io/spring-framework/docs/current/reference/html/integration.html#cache\n> > \n> > current implementation contains hard-coded configuration and no cache invalidation mechanism.\n> > not reliable\n> \n> not sure what do you mean by not \"reliable\".. \n> But indeed we could Caffeine, which has better performance, and supports annotations. that I guess is what you want\n\nmy bad didn't see the put for cache update.\n\nanyway there are still the issues with this implementation:\n\n1) the cache serves the get schema context by dataspace and schema set name\nwhich is a rare case, which returns data for ui (exact case is still unknown yet);\nfrom other hand for frequent expected case - get schema context by dataspace and anchor name -\nthis cache still requires extra db query, to find out which schema set is needed..\nit means we need to cache anchor to schema set name mapping as well, then only this \ncache became useful, then this should be implemented as a separate artifact, not mixed with\nservice logic\n\n2) the cache behavior is quite inflexible, it's unclear how to adopt it for different scenarios\ntaking into account the schema set and/or data update frequency, \n. the caching should be configurable",
        "patchset_number": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "0791632eae83058c1eaa22c8537e7c5133b296a6",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 6639,
          "name": "Toine Siebelink",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "toine.siebelink@est.tech",
          "username": "ToineSiebelink"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2021-01-18 13:29:23.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n> Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1\n> \n> (1 comment)\n> \n> > Patch Set 3:\n> > \n> > > Patch Set 3:\n> > > \n> > > spring framework provides configurable, easy to apply caching\n> > > https://docs.spring.io/spring-framework/docs/current/reference/html/integration.html#cache\n> > > \n> > > current implementation contains hard-coded configuration and no cache invalidation mechanism.\n> > > not reliable\n> > \n> > not sure what do you mean by not \"reliable\".. \n> > But indeed we could Caffeine, which has better performance, and supports annotations. that I guess is what you want\n> \n> my bad didn't see the put for cache update.\n> \n> anyway there are still the issues with this implementation:\n> \n> 1) the cache serves the get schema context by dataspace and schema set name\n> which is a rare case, which returns data for ui (exact case is still unknown yet);\n> from other hand for frequent expected case - get schema context by dataspace and anchor name -\n> this cache still requires extra db query, to find out which schema set is needed..\n> it means we need to cache anchor to schema set name mapping as well, then only this \n> cache became useful, then this should be implemented as a separate artifact, not mixed with\n> service logic\n> \n> 2) the cache behavior is quite inflexible, it's unclear how to adopt it for different scenarios\n> taking into account the schema set and/or data update frequency, \n> . the caching should be configurable\n\nHi Ruslan on the point of what we are caching, we cannot cache by Anchor as an anchor can be re-created with different schemas set. So we do rely on a call to the persistence layer to get the current schema set name/id. It will be a frequent call I agree but it is small and will rely on the built in optimization of the DB for this. But the schema Ste is 'immutable' and it makes sense to cache this (actually much longer then the initial proposal, but w can tune that later)",
        "patchset_number": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "99dfe81a05b1f7e61514281a9bb4182b976632cf",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 6639,
          "name": "Toine Siebelink",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "toine.siebelink@est.tech",
          "username": "ToineSiebelink"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2021-01-18 13:30:42.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nTalked to Claudio by phone and he explained teh caching of Interface YangTextSchemaSourceSet implicitly cache the schemaContext (Yang tools object) I wanted to cache so overall I am good with this solution\n\nNo time for detailed review right now though...",
        "patchset_number": 3
      },
